******
[1] Panama comment
Date: Sun 22 Oct 2017
From: Jan Clement <jan.clement.dr@telenet.be> [edited]


In summary, this 10-year-old child in Panama had acute fever, a "sickle cell-like presentation", and an increasing degree of thrombocytopenia, prompting hantavirus serology, which turned out positive. If the sickle cells appear to be in fact schistocytes, this might be seen rarely in HFRS infections, and lead to an erroneous diagnosis of haemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS), needing sometimes plasmapheresis-therapy as described in 2 Belgian cases (Keyaerts E, .Ghijsels E, Lemey P, et al. Plasma-exchange-associated IgM-negative hantavirus disease after a camping holiday in Southern France. Clin Infect Dis. 2004 May 15;38(10):1350-6) (Clement J, Lee APK, Verpooten GA, et al. Acute hantavirus infection presenting as haemolytic-uraemic syndrome (HUS): the importance of early clinical diagnosis. Eur J Clin Microbiol Infect Dis. DOI 10.1007/s10096-017-3113-6). High levels of LDH, which are present in virtually any hantavirus infection, can reinforce the diagnostic confusion.

The finding of acute kidney injury (AKI), accompanied or not by some degree of lung involvement (ARDS) - neither of which are mentioned in the Panama report - might add substantially to a final diagnosis. We are not aware however of American reports mentioning the occurrence of schistocytes in the peripheral blood film as an element of early clinical diagnosis of HPS [hantavirus pulmonary syndrome]. Consequently, it would perhaps be wise to exclude serologically an Old World hantavirus infection in this Panama case, in other words, a rat-transmitted Seoul virus (SEOV) infection, which would constitute the 7th such case documented so far in North-America. Another human SEOV case in Meso-America could add further ground to the already formerly found arguments or even evidence of symptomatic human SEOV infections in the New World, as suggested in: Clement J, Neild GH, Maes P, Leirs H, Matthys P and Van Ranst M. Symptomatic Human Hantavirus in the Americas. Emerg Inf Dis 2007;13:345-6 [see section [2] for reference. - CopyEd.AO].

--
Jan Clement, Piet Maes and Marc Van Ranst
Hantavirus Reference Centre
Laboratory of Clinical and Epidemiological Virology & Rega Institute for Medical Research,
